          "body": "Verse 4 is the psalm's turn, and its most expansive moment. David interrupts his imprecation to pray for every person who seeks God — 'let all who seek You rejoice and be glad in You' (v.4). The move from personal enemy-prayer to communal intercession is characteristic of the great Davidic psalms (compare Psalm 22:22-31, where the individual lament becomes universal doxology). Those who 'love Your salvation' are to say *continually* — *tamid*, always, without cessation — 'Let God be magnified.' The word *gadal* (to be made great) is the root of the divine name *El Shaddai* in some traditions and of the priestly blessing in Numbers 6:27. It means not merely that God should be praised but that His actual greatness should be visibly displayed in the world. The believer who is still in the crisis is already calling for God's magnification — not as a condition of rescue but as the appropriate response of those who know what God is like."
