          "body": "The Christian interpreter cannot read Psalm 70 without hearing its resonance in the passion narratives. The enemies who mock with 'Aha, aha!' (v.3) appear verbatim in Psalm 35:21 and 40:15 — and the same mockery is hurled at the crucified Christ by those who pass by (Matthew 27:39-44; Mark 15:29). The *ani* and *evyon* of verse 5 reach their fullest instantiation in the one who was 'despised and forsaken of men, a man of sorrows' (Isaiah 53:3). Augustine, in his commentary on the Psalms, reads Psalm 70 as the voice of the whole Christ — head and body together — crying for urgent deliverance, and notes that Christ's cry from the cross (Matthew 27:46, quoting Psalm 22:1) places Him within the exact genre of the psalms of urgency. This does not dissolve the psalm's original Davidic meaning but deepens it: David's prayer was genuine and historically grounded; it also prefigured the one who would pray the same words in the ultimate extremis, and in whose resurrection every *ani* who cries *chush* finds the answer already given."
