        "title": "Urgent petition — the God who can act now",
        "range": "70:1",
        "excerpt": "O God, hasten to deliver me; O Lord, hasten to my help!",
        "body": "The psalm opens in medias res — no introduction, no historical preamble, no liturgical transition. The first word in the Hebrew is the divine name, the second is the urgent imperative. This compression is the psalm's first theological statement: in acute crisis, the believer knows exactly where to turn, and says so immediately.\n\nThe two verbs of verse 1 are worth distinguishing. 'Hasten to deliver me' uses *natsal* — to snatch, to pull away from danger by force, the verb used when God rescues Israel from Egypt (Exodus 3:8) and when Lot is snatched from Sodom (Genesis 19:16). 'Hasten to my help' uses *ezrah* — the noun of assistance, provision, coming alongside. Together they name two dimensions of divine rescue: the aggressive intervention that overcomes opposition, and the supportive presence that sustains the one rescued. David wants both, and asks for both in the same breath.\n\nThe pairing of divine names — *Elohim* in the first half, *Yehovah* in the second — is not stylistic variation. *Elohim* addresses the God of all power, the Creator whose authority is absolute. *Yehovah* addresses the God of personal covenant, the One who bound Himself to David by oath (2 Samuel 7:8-16). By using both names in a single verse, David holds together God's universal sovereignty and His particular faithfulness. The prayer presses both into service: 'As the God who can do anything, and as the God who has promised to be mine — hasten.'\n\nCalvin notes that the very intensity of the request honors God's freedom: it acknowledges that He is not mechanically obligated, that He has the sovereign option to wait — and precisely because He has that option, David pleads with everything he has that He not exercise it now.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chush* (hasten, hurry) appears only in the Psalter and only in urgent address to God — Psalm 22:19; 38:22; 40:13; 70:1, 5; 71:12. It is emergency vocabulary. *Natsal* = to snatch away from danger, to deliver by overpowering opposition. *Ezrah* = help, assistance — same root as the name *Ezra* and the divine *ezer* (helper) of Genesis 2:18."
